"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830164","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2018-01-31","<p>Otters are now present in each county in England and there have been no reintroductions since the 1990s.</p><p> </p><p>There is little evidence to suggest that otters have a major impact on fish populations in rivers as a whole, though localised impacts in rivers could occur where otters have not previously been present for some time.</p><p> </p><p>We recognise that in some instances otters can adversely affect those who keep ornamental fish, and can damage an individual’s business and affect angling in some still water fisheries. As a result there is provision through the Angling Improvement Fund, administered by the Angling Trust on the Environment Agency’s behalf, to help deliver improvements including projects to protect fisheries from predation. Further information can be found on the Angling Trust’s website at: <a href="http://www.anglingtrust.net/" target="_blank">www.anglingtrust.net</a></p><p> </p><p> </p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2018-01-31T19:16:54.027Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830164/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830164/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830164/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2018-01-24","Otters: Conservation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what steps he has put in place to ensure that the reintroduction of otters does not lead to a serious deterioration in fish stocks.","false","Biography information for Dr David Drew","Stroud","Dr David Drew","124832"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830165","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2018-02-05","<p>The revised National Planning Policy Framework will clearly set out that the developer or ‘agent of change’ should be responsible for mitigating noise impacts and other potential nuisances arising from existing businesses and other organisations, such as churches when locating new development or changing uses nearby. However, noise nuisance complaints in existing developments are not handled through the planning system. They are subject to the provisions of the Environmental Protection Act 1990 and other relevant law.</p><p>We are committed to working across government to further strengthen the ‘agent of change’ principle in policy and guidance.</p>","Esher and Walton","Dominic Raab","124834","2018-02-05T14:35:11.17Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830165/answer","Biography information for Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830165/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830165/answer","Esher and Walton","Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830165/answer/previousversion/37785","Biography information for Dominic Raab","7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2018-01-24","Churches: Bellringing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for Housing, Communities and Local Government, pursuant to the Answer of 15 January 2018 to Question 116503, whether the revised National Planning Policy Framework to include new developments will take account of culture, history and tradition where noise nuisance complaints are made about the continued ringing of church bells and chimes by residents living within existing developments.","false","Biography information for Craig Mackinlay","South Thanet","Craig Mackinlay","124833"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830167","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2018-02-05","<p>The revised National Planning Policy Framework will clearly set out that the developer or ‘agent of change’ should be responsible for mitigating noise impacts and other potential nuisances arising from existing businesses and other organisations, such as churches when locating new development or changing uses nearby. However, noise nuisance complaints in existing developments are not handled through the planning system. They are subject to the provisions of the Environmental Protection Act 1990 and other relevant law.</p><p>We are committed to working across government to further strengthen the ‘agent of change’ principle in policy and guidance.</p>","Esher and Walton","Dominic Raab","124833","2018-02-05T14:35:11.233Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830167/answer","Biography information for Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830167/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830167/answer","Esher and Walton","Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830167/answer/previousversion/37786","Biography information for Dominic Raab","7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2018-01-24","Churches: Bellringing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, pursuant to the Answer of 15 January 2018 to  Question 116503, whether the revised National Planning Policy Framework to include new development will take account of culture, history and tradition where noise nuisance complaints are made about the continued ringing of church bells and chimes by residents living within developments that have changed in use such as where a house has been converted to a Bed and Breakfast.","false","Biography information for Craig Mackinlay","South Thanet","Craig Mackinlay","124834"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830169","Cabinet Office","false","2018-01-31","<p><strong>The Government considered the future of the edited (or open) register in 2013 and concluded that it should be retained. The Government concluded that there are wide societal and economic benefits to the edited register. These include allowing businesses to check the identity and address details of people who wish to purchase their goods or services. The Government saw no convincing evidence that the sale of the edited register - from which anyone can quickly and easily opt out - has a negative impact on registration rates.<br></strong></p>","Norwich North","Chloe Smith",,"2018-01-31T15:23:44.297Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830169/answer","Biography information for Chloe Smith","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830169/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830169/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2018-01-24","Electoral Register","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what recent assessment the Government has made of the potential merits of removing the provision of allowing the sale of the edited electoral register.","false","Biography information for Cat Smith","Lancaster and Fleetwood","Cat Smith","124835"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830170","HM Treasury","false","2018-02-01","<p>The new CDS (Customs Declaration Service) will replace the current customs declaration computer system (CHIEF) in January 2019. CDS will provide businesses engaged in international trade with a robust, modern and flexible customs declaration service.</p><p> </p><p>‘The Customs Future Partnership Paper’ published on 15 August 2017 sets out the Government’s aspirations for future customs arrangements with the EU. The two new models proposed are:</p><p>- A highly streamlined customs arrangement</p><p>- A new customs partnership with the EU</p><p> </p><p>The precise nature of any new customs arrangement will be determined in negotiations with the EU.</p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride",,"2018-02-01T14:47:26.243Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830170/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830170/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830170/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2018-01-24","Customs","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what plans his Department has to increase the efficiency of customs clearance processes.","false","Biography information for Adam Afriyie","Windsor","Adam Afriyie","124836"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830172","Cabinet Office","false","2018-01-31","<p>The Cabinet Office does not hold this information but it is accessible from the Office for National Statistics’ website (www.ons.gov.uk)</p><p> </p>","Norwich North","Chloe Smith",,"2018-01-31T15:45:58.41Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830172/answer","Biography information for Chloe Smith","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830172/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830172/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2018-01-24","Electoral Register","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what proportion of registered voters are listed on the edited register.","false","Biography information for Cat Smith","Lancaster and Fleetwood","Cat Smith","124837"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830174","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2018-01-29","<p>The Chair of the Review of Full Time Social Action requested an extension of one month to complete his report.</p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch",,"2018-01-29T14:27:39.983Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830174/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830174/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830174/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2018-01-24","Youth Social Action Review","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, for what reasons the full-time social action review has been delayed.","false","Biography information for Mr Steve Reed","Croydon North","Mr Steve Reed","124838"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830175","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-02-05","<p>The figures requested are given in the table below.</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p><strong>Initial claims made in 2016-17</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Number of people refused PIP</p></td><td><p>390,200</p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Of whom:</p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p>number of people who had that decision changed at mandatory reconsideration</p></td><td><p>28,500</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>number of people who had a decision changed at a tribunal appeal</p></td><td><p>32,300</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p>Figures are for Great Britain.</p><p>Appeal figures are based upon appeals against mandatory reconsideration decisions. Initial decisions cannot be appealed until a claimant has gone through the mandatory reconsideration process.</p><p>Some decisions which are changed at mandatory reconsideration, and where the claimant continues to appeal for a higher PIP award, are then changed again at tribunal appeal. Therefore the number of people who had a decision changed at mandatory reconsideration and the number of people who had a decision changed at tribunal appeal cannot be added together.</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton","124840 ; 124841","2018-02-05T17:28:42.327Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830175/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830175/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830175/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-01-24","Personal Independence Payment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many people were refused personal independence payment in 2016-17.","false","Biography information for Nick Thomas-Symonds","Torfaen","Nick Thomas-Symonds","124839"
