"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828612","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2018-01-29","<p>The Waste and Resources Action Programme estimates there are 270,000 tonnes of food in the grocery supply chain that may be suitable for redistribution.</p><p> </p><p>We are expecting applications for projects that will make a tangible contribution to volumes redistributed, and provide best examples for wider uptake within the sector.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2018-01-29T18:43:59.643Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828612/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828612/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828612/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2018-01-23","Food: Waste","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, pursuant to the Answer of 22 January 2018 to Question 122438, if he will estimate the amount of food waste that will be prevented as a result of the steps he proposes to take.","false","Biography information for Dr David Drew","Stroud","Dr David Drew","124279"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828613","Scotland Office","false","2018-01-29","<p>We have committed to amend Clause 11 of the Bill in agreement with the Scottish and Welsh Governments. As I have made clear, we had not reached agreement in time to table amendments for Report. Our commitment to amending the Bill is absolute, we have intensified discussions and as these progress we will reflect these by bringing forward changes to the Bill in the House of Lords.</p>","Dumfriesshire, Clydesdale and Tweeddale","David Mundell",,"2018-01-29T17:55:59.067Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828613/answer","Biography information for David Mundell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828613/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828613/answer",,,,,"2","Scotland","Scotland","2018-01-23","Brexit: Scotland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Scotland, pursuant to his oral contribution of 6 December 2017, Official Report, column 1021, on what date officials were first instructed to prepare amendments to Clause 11 of the European Union (Withdrawal) Bill for its Report stage.","false","Biography information for Patrick Grady","Glasgow North","Patrick Grady","124280"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828615","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-01-31","<p>The Foreign Secretary and Russian Foreign Minister Lavrov agreed to work together on North Korea by consistent bilateral engagement on that issue and by effective use of the UN Security Council to maintain pressure on North Korea. The Government believes that as a neighbour and trading partner of North Korea as well as a permanent member of the UN Security Council, Russia has a special responsibility for preserving international peace and security.</p>","Cities of London and Westminster","Mark Field",,"2018-01-31T17:04:42.12Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828615/answer","Biography information for Mark Field","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828615/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828615/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-01-23","North Korea: Nuclear Weapons","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, pursuant to the Answer of 12 January 2018 to Question 121390, what he and his Russian counterpart concluded were the best ways they could work together to tackle the global security issues in relation to North Korea.","false","Biography information for Alan Brown","Kilmarnock and Loudoun","Alan Brown","124281"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828616","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-01-31","<p>​The UK welcomes the unanimous adoption of UNSCR 2397 following North Korea's illegal launch of an intercontinental missile on 28 November 2017. This builds on the tough measures adopted in UNSCR 2375 in September. The Government plans to submit to the UN 1718 DPRK Sanctions Committee its implementation report for UNSCR 2397 within 90 days of the Resolution's adoption date of 22 December 2017. The UK, alongside like-minded partners, is actively lobbying for the urgent and comprehensive enforcement of UN sanctions by the international community.</p>","Cities of London and Westminster","Mark Field",,"2018-01-31T14:18:26.847Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828616/answer","Biography information for Mark Field","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828616/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828616/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-01-23","North Korea: UN Resolutions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, pursuant to the Answer of 12 January 2018 to Question 121390 on North Korea: Nuclear Weapons, what steps he is taking to ensure the full implementation of UNSCR 2379 on North Korea.","false","Biography information for Alan Brown","Kilmarnock and Loudoun","Alan Brown","124282"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828617","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-01-31","<p>The measures outlined in UNSCR 2397 are designed to further constrain oil exports, ban additional sectors of trade with the DPRK, and require member states to remove North Korean overseas workers within 24 months, among other measures. The measures target significant income streams used by the DPRK regime to fund their nuclear and ballistic missile programmes.</p><p>Sanctions take time to have an effect but there are clear signs they are beginning to have a significant impact. Kim Jong Un himself admitted as much in his New Year's address. We need to allow time for results and continue to press for strong and comprehensive implementation by all UN member states.</p>","Cities of London and Westminster","Mark Field",,"2018-01-31T14:19:25.753Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828617/answer","Biography information for Mark Field","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828617/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828617/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-01-23","North Korea: Nuclear Weapons","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, pursuant to the Answer of 12 January 2018 to Question 121391 on North Korea: Nuclear Weapons, what the evidential basis is for the statement that the impact of UNSC sanctions on North Korea are increasingly being felt by the Kim regime.","false","Biography information for Alan Brown","Kilmarnock and Loudoun","Alan Brown","124283"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828619","Ministry of Defence","false","2018-01-29","<p>I refer the hon. Member to the answer I gave to his Question 121389 on 15 January 2018.</p><p>The Secretary of State for Defence is briefed on a regular and frequent basis about the development of North Korean Ballistic Missile capability, as he is on a range of defence issues.</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster",,"2018-01-29T15:01:48.98Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828619/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828619/answer","Hansard Extact Monday 15 January 2018 HOC 121389.docx","North Korea:Nuclear Weapons","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828619/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2018-01-23","North Korea: Guided Weapons","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, pursuant to the Answer of 15 January 2018 to Question 121389, what the latest date was on which he was briefed on the development of North Korean Ballistic Missile capability and the conduct of significant tests.","false","Biography information for Alan Brown","Kilmarnock and Loudoun","Alan Brown","124284"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828620","Ministry of Defence","false","2018-01-30","<p>The UK provided input to the US Nuclear Posture Review as part of our close and regular dialogue with the US Administration. I am not prepared to discuss the details of the UK Government input for the purpose of safeguarding national security.</p>","South Staffordshire","Gavin Williamson",,"2018-01-30T14:16:57.93Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828620/answer","Biography information for Gavin Williamson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828620/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828620/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2018-01-23","USA: Nuclear Weapons","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, pursuant to the Answer of 17 January 2018 to Question 122320 on USA: Nuclear Weapons what views were sought by the US administration; and what response the UK Government provided.","false","Biography information for Alan Brown","Kilmarnock and Loudoun","Alan Brown","124285"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828621","Department for International Trade","false","2018-01-29","<p>The Consumer Electronics Show (CES) is an externally organised event. The Department for International Trade has not made an estimate of companies that attended from France, Israel, and the Netherlands and does not hold data for the Number of UK exhibitors.</p><p>DIT has boosted its support for UK companies exhibiting at CES in 2018, including by supporting more than 50 companies to attend.</p>","Beverley and Holderness","Graham Stuart",,"2018-01-29T17:55:15.553Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828621/answer","Biography information for Graham Stuart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828621/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828621/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2018-01-23","Trade Promotion: Technology","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, what estimate he has made of the number of exhibitors at the Consumer Electronics Show 2017 that came from (a) the UK, (b) France, (c) the Netherlands, and (d) Israel; and what support his Department provided to exhibitors from the UK.","false","Biography information for Chi Onwurah","Newcastle upon Tyne Central","Chi Onwurah","124286"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828622","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2018-01-29","<p>Defra is responsible for endemic disease issues in England. Alongside the Welsh Government and Scottish Government, it sponsors the Animal and Plant Health Agency (APHA), which provides services across Great Britain.</p><p> </p><p>APHA is monitoring the virus in Great Britain and working with veterinary professionals and the cattle and sheep sectors to raise awareness. The Agency works with officials in Northern Ireland and the EU to better understand the disease. It offers testing where there are reasonable grounds to suspect that cattle disease is caused by the virus. Preventing the spread of the disease is difficult as it is spread by midges, however there are two vaccines offering protection against the disease currently licenced in the UK, one of which is currently manufactured.</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2018-01-29T18:03:51.273Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828622/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828622/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828622/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2018-01-23","Schmallenberg Virus: Disease Control","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what steps are being taken to put in place precautions to prevent the spread of the Schmallenberg virus.","false","Biography information for Mr Gregory Campbell","East Londonderry","Mr Gregory Campbell","124287"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828623","Home Office","false","2018-01-30","<p>The Home Office does not hold this information. It is for elected Police and Crime Commissioners and Chief Constables to decide how their force’s resources are deployed and how best to manage their communications with the public.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick  Hurd",,"2018-01-30T15:56:46.49Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828623/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828623/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828623/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-01-23","Police: North West","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department how much was spent on hire cars by each constabulary in the North West in 2016 and 2017; and what steps are being taken to reduce expenditure on such cars.","false","Biography information for Sir Mark Hendrick","Preston","Sir Mark Hendrick","124288"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828624","HM Treasury","false","2018-01-31","<p>The Government is clear that everyone who is entitled to the National Minimum and National Living Wage (NMW) should receive it. Anyone who feels they have been underpaid NMW should contact the Acas helpline on 0300 123 1100. HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC) review all complaints that are referred to them.</p><p> </p><p>HMRC is unable to provide figures on the civil actions where arrears were recovered, as it does not hold this data in a readily available format.</p><p> </p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride",,"2018-01-31T12:11:21.803Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828624/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828624/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828624/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2018-01-23","Minimum Wage: Non-payment","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, pursuant to the Answer of 19 January 2018 to Question 122436, on Minimum Wage, how many of the 532 civil actions initiated since 2010 resulted in the recovery of unpaid minimum wage arrears.","false","Biography information for Caroline Lucas","Brighton, Pavilion","Caroline Lucas","124289"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828625","Ministry of Justice","false","2018-01-29","<p>Supporting victims of crime is a priority for the Government and we have made a commitment to publish a victims strategy in 2018. We are looking at legislative and non-legislative options to give effect to the strategy.</p><p> </p><p>We are engaging widely with victims, victims’ groups and other stakeholders, including but not limited to the Victims’ Commissioner, Criminal Justice Agencies, and the Association of Police and Crime Commissioners.</p>","Bracknell","Dr Phillip Lee",,"2018-01-29T15:24:09.1Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828625/answer","Biography information for Dr Phillip Lee","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828625/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828625/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2018-01-23","Crime: Victims","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, which organisations his Department consulted on the introduction of a victims law; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Gloria De Piero","Ashfield","Gloria De Piero","124290"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828626","Department for Education","false","2018-01-31","<p>Support staff pay is negotiated by local authorities and academies. We are aware of the offer and will continue to support schools in managing their budgets.</p><p> </p><p>The new National Funding Formula, backed by £1.3 billion of additional investment, will allocate, as a minimum, £3,500 per pupil for all primary schools, and £4,800 per pupil for all secondary schools, by 2019-20. As the independent Institute for Fiscal Studies has confirmed, overall schools funding is being protected at a national level in real terms per pupil over the next two years. Alongside this substantial investment, we are committed to helping schools to improve their efficiency, so that they can continue to improve pupil outcomes and promote social mobility.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2018-01-31T16:58:44.757Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828626/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828626/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828626/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-01-23","Schools: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what assessment he has made of the potential effect of the 2018-19 local government pay offer on school finances.","false","Biography information for Ian Austin","Dudley North","Ian Austin","124291"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828628","Department for Education","false","2018-01-31","<p>Support staff pay is negotiated by local authorities and academies themselves. The Department has no remit in this area and as such has not held any recent meetings on support staff pay.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2018-01-31T16:05:16.797Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828628/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828628/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828628/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-01-23","Schools: Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what recent meetings he has held with (a) schools, (b) the Local Government Association and (c) trade unions on school support staff pay.","false","Biography information for Ian Austin","Dudley North","Ian Austin","124292"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828629","Department for Education","false","2018-01-31","<p>My right hon. Friend the Secretary of State for Education routinely discusses matters of shared interest with Cabinet colleagues, including my right hon. Friend the Chancellor of the Exchequer. The Department will shortly publish evidence on the affordability of increases to teacher pay as part of the input to the School Teachers’ Review Body consideration on teachers’ pay for 2018/19.</p><p>In July 2017 the Government announced an additional £1.3 billion for schools and high needs across 2018-19 and 2019-20, in addition to the schools budget set at the Spending Review 2015. This means funding per pupil will be maintained in real terms for the next two years. Following the Government’s announcement in September 2017, under the national funding formula school funding will be distributed based on the individual needs and characteristics of every school in England.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2018-01-31T14:38:44.94Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828629/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828629/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828629/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-01-23","Schools: Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what recent discussions he has held with the Chancellor of the Exchequer on the schools' wage costs.","false","Biography information for Ian Austin","Dudley North","Ian Austin","124293"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828630","Department for Education","false","2018-01-31","<p>The Department has not recently undertaken or commissioned any research on school support staff pay, as it is negotiated by local authorities and academies themselves.</p><p> </p><p>In 2011, the Department did publish a topic note on support staff, which is available here: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/school-support-staff-topic-paper" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/school-support-staff-topic-paper</a>.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2018-01-31T14:58:01.583Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828630/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828630/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828630/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-01-23","Schools: Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what research his Department has (a) undertaken and (b) commissioned on the adequacy of the level of school support staff pay.","false","Biography information for Ian Austin","Dudley North","Ian Austin","124294"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828631","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2018-01-31","<p>The Government is committed to strengthening the rural economy, setting the right conditions for businesses to grow and thrive.</p><p> </p><p>The Industrial Strategy, published in November 2017, includes steps that will benefit rural businesses, such as access to finance and improved digital connectivity.</p><p> </p><p>The Rural Productivity Plan, published in 2015, set out a 10-point plan to boost rural economies. As part of this, enterprise zones have been established in rural areas.</p><p>Last year, a new enterprise zone was created to help support local growth in Whitehill and Bordon, in particular local start-ups, SMEs, and high-growth businesses. These businesses will be able to benefit from the Bordon innovation centre newly opened in November, as part of the wider TechForest initiative.</p><p> </p><p>The £3.5 billion Rural Development Programme for England supports farmers, foresters and rural businesses and communities. In Hampshire, 41 projects worth a total of £1,296,519 have been agreed to date.</p><p> </p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2018-01-31T15:42:00.9Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828631/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828631/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828631/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2018-01-23","Economic Situation: Hampshire","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what his steps his Department is taking to support the rural economy in Hampshire.","false","Biography information for Mr Ranil Jayawardena","North East Hampshire","Mr Ranil Jayawardena","124295"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828632","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2018-01-31","<p>Supporting UK businesses to export more is a top priority for this government. Supporting the exports of companies, such as Marston’s Breweries and the 40 food and drink businesses currently being supported by the Department for International Trade (DIT) team in Hampshire, will be an important driver of growth in the food and drink sector, allowing it to become more resilient, competitive and profitable.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p>However, our work through the Food is GREAT campaign continues to raise the profile and reputation of British food and drink. Delivered in partnership with DIT, VisitBritain and FCO, this Defra led campaign will benefit food and drink exporters from across the UK, including Hampshire, to access new export opportunities.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2018-01-31T17:31:38.203Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828632/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828632/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828632/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2018-01-23","Food: Hampshire","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what assessment he has made of the performance of the Great British Food Unit in opening up new markets for food and drink from Hampshire.","false","Biography information for Mr Ranil Jayawardena","North East Hampshire","Mr Ranil Jayawardena","124296"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828634","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2018-01-29","<p>The Insolvency Service produces quarterly statistics on the number of new insolvencies for companies and individuals in England and Wales. The most recent statistics, covering the period October to December 2017, which include a comparison with previous periods, were published on Friday 26 January 2018 on Gov.uk.</p>","Burton","Andrew Griffiths",,"2018-01-29T15:45:28.197Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828634/answer","Biography information for Andrew Griffiths","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828634/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828634/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2018-01-23","Insolvency","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what assessment his Department has made of trends in the level of business insolvencies in the last two years.","false","Biography information for Jo Stevens","Cardiff Central","Jo Stevens","124297"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828635","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2018-02-05","<p>Landlords are expected to keep their properties free of potential hazards and safe for tenants. Where they fail to do so, local authorities have strong powers under the Housing Act 2004 to require necessary improvements to be made. In the rental market, the extent to which the cost of keeping a property safe is reflected in the rent is a commercial decision to be taken by individual landlords, along with other relevant facts such as the size and location of the property and the level of demand in the area.</p><p>Where the tenants are leaseholders they can seek free initial advice, funded by the Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government, from the Leaseholder Advisory Service (LEASE). In addition, Section 20 of the Landlord and Tenant Act 1985 consultation process ensures that leaseholders contributing towards the upkeep and maintenance of the building where they live have input into how their money is spent.</p><p>The government would like to see building owners doing all they can to protect leaseholders from the costs of interim measures and cladding remediation – either by funding it themselves or looking at alternative routes such as insurance claims, warranties or legal action.</p><p>The department is keeping the situation under review.</p>","Esher and Walton","Dominic Raab",,"2018-02-05T14:42:00.69Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828635/answer","Biography information for Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828635/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828635/answer","Esher and Walton","Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828635/answer/previousversion/37769","Biography information for Dominic Raab","7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2018-01-23","Housing: Safety","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, what steps he is taking to ensure the costs of making buildings safe are not passed on to tenants.","false","Biography information for Jo Stevens","Cardiff Central","Jo Stevens","124298"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828636","Wales Office","false","2018-01-29","<p>The Government is having intensive discussions with the Welsh Government on the European Union (Withdrawal) Bill with a view to securing the legislative consent of the National Assembly for Wales to the Bill.</p><p> </p><p>My Rt honourable Friend the Chancellor of the Duchy of Lancaster and I are meeting the First Minister later this week as part of those ongoing discussions.</p>","Vale of Glamorgan","Alun Cairns",,"2018-01-29T16:22:16.547Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828636/answer","Biography information for Alun Cairns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828636/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828636/answer",,,,,"28","Wales","Wales","2018-01-23","Brexit: Wales","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Wales, what recent discussions he has had with the First Minister of Wales on legislative consent for the European Withdrawal Bill.","false","Biography information for Jo Stevens","Cardiff Central","Jo Stevens","124299"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828637","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2018-01-29","<p>The level of interest generated by the announcement of the prospective loan of the Bayeux Tapestry shows the great appetite of the UK public for our culture and history. I note the expression of interest of the National Museum of Wales, and many other fine institutions. A decision on where to host the tapestry when it comes to the UK will be made in full consultation with the authorities of the Bayeux Museum. Our primary consideration must be to ensure that the Tapestry is housed in an appropriate venue and that it is accessible by as many people as possible.</p>","Northampton North","Michael Ellis",,"2018-01-29T14:46:17.86Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828637/answer","Biography information for Michael Ellis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828637/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828637/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2018-01-23","Bayeux Tapestry","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, if the Government will make an assessment of the potential merits of temporarily displaying the Bayeux Tapestry in the National Museum of Wales; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Jo Stevens","Cardiff Central","Jo Stevens","124300"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828638","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2018-01-29","<p>The UK Shared Prosperity Fund will be a domestic programme of investment to boost productivity and reduce economic inequality across the country, following our departure from the European Union. We will consult widely on the design of the UK Shared Prosperity Fund in 2018 and will work with the devolved administrations prior to the public consultation.</p>","Rossendale and Darwen","Jake Berry",,"2018-01-29T11:08:08.733Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828638/answer","Biography information for Jake Berry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828638/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828638/answer",,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2018-01-23","EU Grants and Loans","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, when the Government's consultation on the Shared Prosperity Fund will open; and when the Government plans to publish a response to that consultation.","false","Biography information for Jo Stevens","Cardiff Central","Jo Stevens","124301"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828640","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2018-01-29","<p>I refer the Rt Hon member to the answer of 117167. The pilot is due to commence in the Midlands in summer 2018.</p><p> </p>","South Derbyshire","Mrs Heather Wheeler",,"2018-01-29T14:57:30.75Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828640/answer","Biography information for Mrs Heather Wheeler","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828640/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828640/answer",,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2018-01-23","Right to Buy Scheme","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, how much funding has been allocated by his Department to the voluntary right to buy pilot process for each of the next five years; and how much of that funding has been spent.","false","Biography information for John Healey","Wentworth and Dearne","John Healey","124302"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828641","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2018-01-29","<p>The voluntary Right to Buy regional pilot will give thousands more housing association tenants the opportunity to enjoy the benefits of home ownership. The Government is currently engaging with the National Housing Federation and the specific housing associations in the Midlands and more details on the pilot will be announced in due course.</p>","South Derbyshire","Mrs Heather Wheeler",,"2018-01-29T14:58:21.52Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828641/answer","Biography information for Mrs Heather Wheeler","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828641/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828641/answer",,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2018-01-23","Right to Buy Scheme","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, what estimate he has made of the number of houses that will be sold in each of the next five years as a result of the voluntary right to buy pilots.","false","Biography information for John Healey","Wentworth and Dearne","John Healey","124303"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828642","Home Office","false","2018-01-29","<p>The Home Office has rolled out biometric residence permits to persons subject to immigration control to make it easier for them to evidence their status and simpler for employers to check their right to work.</p><p>We remain committed to simplifying the system of right to work checks for migrants and employers, including through the development of automated checking tools.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline  Nokes",,"2018-01-29T16:17:36.627Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828642/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828642/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828642/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-01-23","Immigrants: Employment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, pursuant to the Answer of 10 January 2018 to Question 120539 on Immigrants: Employment, what steps her Department is taking to simplify the employer checking service  for (a) perspective employees and (b) employers.","false","Biography information for Gill Furniss","Sheffield, Brightside and Hillsborough","Gill Furniss","124304"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828644","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-01-29","<p>We are closely following developments in Afrin in north-western Syria. The Foreign Secretary and I have been in contact with Turkish Foreign Minister Çavuşoğlu to discuss the Turkish operation in Afrin. We recognise Turkey's legitimate interest in the security of its borders. We have urged them to avoid any escalation in violence and to seek to protect civilians. It remains in our shared interest to focus on achieving a political settlement that ends the war and suffering, and provides stability for all Syrians and the wider region.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2018-01-29T16:07:01.69Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828644/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828644/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828644/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-01-23","Syria: Armed Conflict","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent assessment he has made of the security situation in Afrin district, northern Syria.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","124305"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828645","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-01-29","<p>We are closely following developments in Afrin in north-western Syria, and the Foreign Secretary and other Foreign and Commonwealth Office Ministers are in regular contact with their Turkish counterparts. We recognise Turkey's legitimate interest in the security of its borders. We have urged them to avoid any escalation in violence and to seek to protect civilians. It remains in our shared interest to focus on achieving a political settlement that ends the war and suffering, and provides stability for all Syrians and the wider region.</p>","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan","124312","2018-01-29T17:32:06.097Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828645/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828645/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828645/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-01-23","Syria: Armed Conflict","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent discussions he has had with his Turkish counterpart on Turkish military operations underway in Afrin district, northern Syria.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","124306"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828646","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-01-29","<p>As part of implementing the MH Upper Tribunal judgment, the Department for Work and Pensions will carry out an administrative exercise in order to ensure that claimants receive the correct award. We will be going through all cases in receipt of PIP and all decisions made since the judgment in MH to identify anyone who may be entitled to more as a result of the judgment. This review will include claimants who are currently receiving the standard rate of the PIP mobility component and experience psychological distress.</p><p>The Department will directly contact anyone who is affected and additional payments will be backdated to the effective date in each claim. The effective date will be either the date of the claim or the date of the MH judgment (November 2016), whichever is the later date. Claimants do not need to write to DWP in order to receive the correct award.</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton",,"2018-01-29T17:22:15.957Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828646/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828646/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828646/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-01-23","Personal Independence Payment: Mental Health","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, with reference to Written Statement of 19 January 2018, HCWS414, whether applicants will be entitled to a reassessment if they were given the standard rate of the PIP mobility component after the February 2017 changes to PIP regulations, where the cause of the claim was psychological distress.","false","Biography information for Debbie Abrahams","Oldham East and Saddleworth","Debbie Abrahams","124307"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828647","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-01-29","<p>We are working with stakeholders to change the PIP assessment guide so that we can implement the judgment. Once we have completed this exercise we will be carrying out an administrative exercise to review cases that may be eligible and ensure that claimants receive the correct award. This will be a complex exercise and of considerable scale, as we will be reconsidering approximately 1.6 million claims. Whilst we will be working at pace to complete this exercise it is important that we get it right.</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton",,"2018-01-29T14:46:42.69Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828647/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828647/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828647/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-01-23","Personal Independence Payment: Mental health","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, with reference to the Written Statement of 19 January 2018, HCWS414, what the timetable is for claimants to be informed if they are entitled to a back payment.","false","Biography information for Debbie Abrahams","Oldham East and Saddleworth","Debbie Abrahams","124308"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828648","Ministry of Defence","false","2018-01-30","<p>Security remains a priority for the Department and no decisions will be taken which would compromise the security of our personnel, information and assets.</p><p>The Ministry of Defence intends to fully explore and develop options, for the future provision of an effective unarmed guarding service for Defence establishments throughout the UK that achieves maximum value for money for tax payers. It is too early to determine how this service will be provided in the future.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2018-01-30T15:08:34.333Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828648/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828648/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828648/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2018-01-23","Ministry of Defence Guard Service","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what his Department’s plans are for the Ministry of Defence Guard Service.","false","Biography information for Michelle Donelan","Chippenham","Michelle Donelan","124309"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828650","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-01-29","<p>​Afrin is largely under the de facto control of the Kurdish PYD party. We have some human rights concerns about the PYD's governance of areas it controls although these are not as severe as the human rights situation in areas held by the Syrian regime. We have particular concern about the PYD's intolerance of political opposition and reports of harassment and arbitrary detention of political opponents. NGOs and others have also raised concerns about human rights protection of those in custody under PYD authority. We are following the situation in Afrin closely since the announcement of the Turkish operation there. The UK is committed to working closely with Turkey and other Allies to find solutions in Syria that provide stability, refrain from escalating the situation and protect Turkey's security interests.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2018-01-29T16:27:10.167Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828650/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828650/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828650/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-01-23","Syria: Kurds","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent assessment he has made of the human rights  situation of Kurdish communities in the Afrin district, northern Syria.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","124310"
